The paper deals with the problem of variable-length channel resolvability, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the encoding of mixed sources, which falls under the category of information-theoretic privacy (cs.ITP). The analysis of the achievable length rate involves the use of probability theory and statistics, which are topics in data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper discusses the application of the results to variable-length source coding, which is a topic in signal processing (cs.SI).
